Let me introduce you this website and myself in this post! And feel free to write comments!

My name is Long Do Hai, I am a web developer living in the middle of Europe - Czech Republic. I came from Vietnam, and lived here for over 18 years. I love technology, travelling, exotic fruit, music, new cultures, and that's what I'm going to write about on this website.

There are 4 categories you can browse. What are they about...

In the technology section I will share my tips and tricks about building a website, mostly in Symfony and Laravel frameworks. If you are a developer, I'm sure you had a time when you faced a problem that took you a while to solve. I spend hours and hours every week just googling and browsing stackoverflow. I will try to post things I find interesting or¬†useful.

Life hacks are also tips and tricks. These articles will be mostly about troubles I faced in my life. Most of them I solved in a good way. Some of them are embarassing, or funny. And some of them I could have solved better. I hope these will help someone, or at least be fun to read.

Each year I travel to another country, and these memories, stories and knowledges are one of the happiest in my life. So why don't share them with you? Before the journey I often¬†read other people's blogs, who had already visited that place, and I really enjoy reading them. I would like my articles to help someone in this way as well.

And the last category, spontanneous, will contain articles about things that just came randomly to my mind. Sometimes It's worth writing them down...

This blog was created as a school work for my subject.";s:10:"post_title";s:10:"Hi there !";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:4:"open";s:11:"ping_status";s:4:"open";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:11:"hello-world";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2016-03-18 11:12:41";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2016-03-18 11:12:41";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:26:"http://myknowledge.eu/?p=1";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:4:"post";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:1;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:2:"20";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"1";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2016-04-08 08:54:26";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2016-04-08 08:54:26";s:12:"post_content";s:1458:"I've been living in the Czech Republic for some time and from time to time people would just ask me, how many languages do I speak, and how to say some word in my native language. So, this idea just came across my mind...to write an article about languages. Hope you like it.

The first language I speak is vietnamese. That's because I was born in Hanoi, and also was raised by my grandparents. I can speak vietnamese fluently most of the time, but when it comes to a more advanced topic, my parents have to explain it to me using just basic vocabulary in order to understand it. Also, there are several¬†dialects in vietnamese - some of them are very similar to the "official", but there are ones I don't understand at all. Sometimes I listen to vietnamese music, and even sing karaoke in vietnamese, but to be honest, I don't usually understand the meaning of the songs. I primarily use vietnamese to talk to my parents, and my relatives.

The second one is the Czech language. I've been living here since I was 4 years old and my parents wanted me to speak Czech fluently, so I wouldn't be struggling as they did when they came to this new country. So they sent me to a Czech nanny. I remember the first time I met the nanny's family - I was so scared of the new environment. The food was sooo different that I just refused to eat and behaved badly, so the nanny was yelling at me in a language I didn't know back then. And that's how I learned Czech.";s:10:"post_title";s:15:"I am trilingual";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:4:"open";s:11:"ping_status";s:4:"open";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:15:"i-am-trilingual";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2016-04-15 09:38:57";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2016-04-15 09:38:57";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:27:"http://myknowledge.eu/?p=20";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:4:"post";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:2;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:2:"55";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"1";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2016-04-29 09:03:07";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2016-04-29 09:03:07";s:12:"post_content";s:1826:"Let's be honest. I am a geek. I have a lot of tech stuff at home, and in this article I'd like to share what I use. As a web developer I use my computer every day. I am a Mac user, I've got a 27" iMac and a Macbook Pro for doing stuff when I'm travelling. I also use a Samsung external monitor. My mouse is a Roccat Kone XTD and I use the keyboard bundled with my iMac.

<img class="size-medium wp-image-65 aligncenter" src="http://myknowledge.eu/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/imac-gallery5-2015-300x230.jpeg" alt="imac-gallery5-2015" width="300" height="230" />

By the way, the mouse is really great, I definitely remommend this mouse if you are right handed. I will post a detailed review of this mouse in the future.

For speakers, recently I bought the Harman Kardon Soundsticks Wireless, and they sound amazing. I love bass, and these speakers have excellent subwoofers. And they also have a nice, futuristic look.

<img class="size-medium wp-image-64 aligncenter" src="http://myknowledge.eu/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/B008YFD5G4.HERO_LARGE-300x300.jpg" alt="B008YFD5G4.HERO_LARGE" width="300" height="300" />

In the past I experimented doing some iOS programming in Objective-C and Swift. That's why I use an iPhone and iPad. Currently I have an iPhone SE and it suits me really well, as I have small hands. Recently I also bought the Apple Watch, and it's working great so far. I love the feeling when it does the haptic feedback thing. Since then I don't have to check my phone everytime it vibrates in my pocket.

<img class="size-medium wp-image-66 aligncenter" src="http://myknowledge.eu/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/s38sg-sbbk-sel-201603-254x300.jpeg" alt="s38sg-sbbk-sel-201603" width="254" height="300" />

And that's basically it! Next time I will share what software I use, both at home and at work.";s:10:"post_title";s:18:"What tech do I use";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:4:"open";s:11:"ping_status";s:4:"open";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:18:"what-tech-do-i-use";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2016-05-13 07:17:49";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2016-05-13 07:17:49";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:27:"http://myknowledge.eu/?p=55";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:4:"post";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:3;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:2:"68";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"1";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2016-05-13 09:00:06";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2016-05-13 09:00:06";s:12:"post_content";s:1431:"In the last article I mentioned that I will write what software I use. I guess now it's the time. Currently, I work as a junior web developer and tester, so primarily I will focus on the tools that we use in the company.

Let's start with PHPStorm. PHPStorm is one of the best IDEs out there, made by a company called JetBrains. I think it is a Czech company, but I'm not sure. It has almost every feature that we need, including Composer integration, version control systems like Git, SVN built in, and most importantly, a great Intellisense. The features can also be customized and added via plugins, that really helps with my overall workflow. Plugins I use are Symfony, Laravel, PHP Annotations and some related to Nette - Latte, Neon.

Next, as a localhost server we use XAMPP, and because at home I use OS X, I also use MAMP. It's the easiest way how to set up a virtual host.

To connect securely to Git server we use Putty SSH and Pageant. I personally didn't know about this type of authorization before I started working.

As a text editor I use Visual Studio Code, or Atom. Believe it or not, VS Code is really great!

For compiling Less we use WinLess. I don't like this approach, since I used to use Sass in combination with Gulp, but since the company uses Less, I must too.

Then we use standard corporate tools from Microsoft, like Outlook, Lync, this kind of stuff.

Let me know if I missed anything.";s:10:"post_title";s:29:"What software I use every day";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:4:"open";s:11:"ping_status";s:4:"open";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:29:"what-software-i-use-every-day";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2016-05-13 09:01:46";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2016-05-13 09:01:46";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:27:"http://myknowledge.eu/?p=68";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:4:"post";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:4;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:2:"73";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"1";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2016-05-13 09:10:52";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2016-05-13 09:10:52";s:12:"post_content";s:1903:"<h6 style="text-align: center;">This article is about how I applied for a visa to US. It's aimed primarily for Czech people, that's why this article will be in Czech.</h6>
